Figure 0 shows the two-panel reliability diagram of all six conditions. The upper panel depicts calibration curves; the lower panel depicts the predicted-probability histograms. The SMOTE Ensemble (T0) has the typical over-confident behavior of resampled 
\hich\af0\dbch\af31505\loch\f0 classifiers: at low predicted probabilities (0.05}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs20 \ltrch\fcs0 \fs20\cf23\insrsid2370223 -}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs20 \ltrch\fcs0 \fs20\cf23\insrsid2370223\charrsid2370223 \hich\af0\dbch\af31505\loch\f0 
0.25) the curve is above the diagonal, overestimating the perceived risk; in the high-probability range (0.60}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs20 \ltrch\fcs0 \fs20\cf23\insrsid2370223 -}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs20 \ltrch\fcs0 \fs20\cf23\insrsid2370223\charrsid2370223 
\hich\af0\dbch\af31505\loch\f0 0.90) the curve is flat, underestimating the actual risk. This bias is common to the three oversampling variants (T0}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs20 \ltrch\fcs0 \fs20\cf23\insrsid2370223 -}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs20 \ltrch\fcs0 
\fs20\cf23\insrsid2370223\charrsid2370223 \hich\af0\dbch\af31505\loch\f0 
T2) to varying extents. T3 (Cost-Sensitive) significantly decreases the over-confidence in the low-risk area but has a slight curvature at the 65% clinical action point. T4 (Platt) fixes the mid-range }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs20 \ltrch\fcs0 
\fs20\cf23\insrsid2370223\charrsid2370223 \hich\af0\dbch\af31505\loch\f0 curvature but}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs20 \ltrch\fcs0 \fs20\cf23\insrsid2370223\charrsid2370223 \hich\af0\dbch\af31505\loch\f0 
 introduces a small over-confidence below 20% because of the parametric sigmoid assumption. T5 (Isotonic) best follows the diagonal over the entire probability range, including the 65% clinical decision zone, which proves that isotonic regression is the a
\hich\af0\dbch\af31505\loch\f0 ppropriate calibration procedure to use with this ensemble, where the score distribution is non-sigmoidal.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs20 \ltrch\fcs0 \fs20\cf23\insrsid11291418 
